library(GrandCanyonSandbaR)

    Find the Nearest Upstream Gage to any riverMile

    This function is critical in caluclating the lag time, or the time it takes flow to travel from the nearest upstream gage to the location of your sandbar site

    
riverMile = 167.3
getNearestUpstreamGage(riverMile, messages = TRUE)
#> The Nearest Upstream Gage to riverMile:167.3 is: National -- at riverMile: 166
#> Returning index for nearest upstream gage in data frame: GageList:5
#> [1] 5

    Calculate the Lagtime between any point in the canyon and the nearest upstream gage

    once lag time is calculated, local hydrographs and flow patterns can be calculated for each site. (comming soon)

    
out <- findLagtime(rivermile = 32.9, message = TRUE)
#> [1] "Selected river mile = 32.9 ;nearest gage = ThirtyMile ;distance in rivermiles = -2.9;lag hours = 0.659699999999999"
print(out)
#> $lagtime
#> [1] "2374.92s (~39.58 minutes)"
#> 
#> $nearest_gage
#> [1] "ThirtyMile"
#> 
#> $nearest_gage_index
#> [1] 2

    Plot an interactive Hydrograph

    The interactivity is helpful for zooming in and looking at flow patterns, NOTE: this function uses dygraphs which requires the discharge data to be in xts format

    data("SampleQ_xts_cfs")
 plotInteractiveHydrograph(Qdat = SampleQ_xts_cfs,
   title= "Colorado River Discharge at Lees Ferry",
   subtitle = "October 3rd 2014 - October 11th 2014")

    plot stage discharge relationships at one of the sandbar sites

    This function takes the measured stage discharge data at each site from previous surveys and fits a a generalized power law model then outputs the model for use in other ways..

    
model <- fitGeneralizedPowerLawModel('0307R') # Assumes '0307R' is a valid site in SandbarSites
#> Valid sitename
#> Using Package bdrc -- Bayesian Discharge Rating Curve
#> Using bdrc::gplm.fit to fit a generalized power law model for stage-discharge at: 0307R Sandbar
#> This may take a few moments
#> Warning in gplm.inference(y = log(Q), h = h, c_param = c_param, h_max = h_max,
#> : Dataset lacks measurements near point of zero flow and thus the model infers
#> its upper bound (see c_upper in run_info).
#> Plotting Rating Curve

    Next we will estimate discharge at a specified site using the stage discharge model

    we do this by generating a grid of equally spaced elevation increments and applying the model to calculate the likely discharge with lower and upper bounds for discharge in CFS and CMS

    

grid <- GenerateEquallySpacedStageDischarge(sitename = '2201R') # Assumes '2201R' is a valid site in SandbarSites
#> Valid sitename
#> Valid sitename
#> Using Package bdrc -- Bayesian Discharge Rating Curve
#> Using bdrc::gplm.fit to fit a generalized power law model for stage-discharge at: 2201R Sandbar
#> This may take a few moments
#> Plotting Rating Curve
#> Generating equally spaced grid of elevations
#> from: 394.752 Meters to: 401.033 Meters
#> increments of: 0.001 Meters

    discharge_info <- find_Q_from_WSE('2201R', grid, 400.002) # Assumes '2201R' is a valid site and grid is defined
#> Valid sitename
#> Valid sitename
#> Minimum SD Elevation for site:2201R = 394.752
#> Maximum SD Elevation for site:2201R = 401.033
#> [1] "valid elevation for site:2201R"
#> [1] 5251
print(discharge_info)
#>      Elevation CMS_lower CMS_median CMS_upper CFS_lower CFS_median CFS_upper
#> 5251   400.002  1840.175   2104.796  2411.229   64985.2   74330.19   85151.8
